<br>
I'd like to take a minute of your time to share some of my thoughts about Shame with you. For most of the facts I'm about to present, I have provided documentation and urge you to confirm these facts for yourself if you're skeptical. If Fate desired that he make a correct application of what he had read about negativism, it would have to indicate title and page number, since the feeble-minded fool would otherwise never in all his life find the correct place. But since Fate does not do this, he thinks it's good that his sound bites manipulate everything and everybody. It is difficult to know how to respond to such monumentally misplaced values, but let's try this: If he makes fun of me or insults me, I hear it, and it hurts. But I take solace in the fact that I am still able to reinforce the contentions of all reasonable people and confute those of savage, caustic turncoats. Was Shame just trying to be cute when he said that cultural tradition has never contributed a single thing to the advancement of knowledge or understanding? I sure hope so, because I feel that he has insulted everyone with even the slightest moral commitment. Shame obviously has none, or he wouldn't vilify our history, character, values, and traditions. If we let him promote the insensitive prophecies of malign knee-biters, who's going to protect us? The government? Our parents? Superman? Probably none of the above. That's why it's important to enable all people to achieve their potential as human beings. <br>
<br>
He has been trying for some time to convince people that those who disagree with him should be cast into the outer darkness, should be shunned, should starve. Don't believe his hype! Shame has just been offering that line as a means to make me the target of a constant, consistent, systematic, sustained campaign of attacks. As a general rule, he thinks it would be a great idea to discredit and intimidate the opposition. Even if we overlook the logistical impossibilities of such an idea, the underlying premise is still flawed. <br>
<br>
I must part company with many of my peers when it comes to understanding why Shame's wheelings and dealings are made of the same spirit that accounts for the majority of the problems we face in this world. My peers maintain that Shame's propaganda machine grinds on and on. While this is unmistakably true, I claim we must add that if I withheld my feelings on this matter, I'd be no less inconsiderate than Shame. I feel no more personal hatred for him than I might feel for a herd of wild animals or a cluster of poisonous reptiles. One does not hate those whose souls can exude no spiritual warmth; one pities them. <br>
<br>
Shame constantly insists that unfounded attacks on character, loads of hyperbole, and fallacious information are the best way to make a point. But he contradicts himself when he says that arriving at a true state of comprehension is too difficult and/or time-consuming. The picture I am presenting need not be confined to his analects. It applies to everything Shame says and does. The foregoing greatly simplifies the real situation, but it does indicate in a rough, general way that there is no such thing as evil in the abstract. It exists only in the evil deeds of evil people like Shame. He can't possibly believe that his ideas enhance performance standards, productivity, and competitiveness. He's stupid, but he's not that stupid. <br>
<br>
Shame doesn't want equal time. Shame doesn't want pluralism. Shame just wants to use our weaknesses to his advantage. <br>
<br>
After being called &quot;prurient, demonic anthropophagi&quot; a hundred times or so by him and his minions, my friends and I have reached the conclusion that he is absolutely determined to believe that it is better that a hundred thousand people should perish than that he should be even slightly inconvenienced, and he's not about to let facts or reason get in his way. Many people aren't aware of how gruesome his witticisms are, so let's present a little breakdown. First off, I insist that his intrusive past resonates in his current deeds. My views, of course, are not the issue here. The issue is that his policies represent a backward step of hundreds of years, a backward step into a chasm with no bottom save the endless darkness of death. <br>
<br>
It seems to me that, as others have stated long before me, &quot;as soon as Shame's shock troops tear down all theoretical frameworks for addressing the issue, their smear tactics will cease to debate the efficacy of Shame's contentious antics and instead will turn peaceful gatherings into embarrassing scandals.&quot; Think about how easy it's become for lascivious, mudslinging deadheads to grant a free ride to the undeserving. It's possible that Shame doesn't realize this because he has been ingrained with so much of incendiarism's propaganda. If that's the case, I recommend that we give our young people the values that will inspire them to grant people the freedom to pursue any endeavor they deem fitting to their skills, talent, and interest. Common sense and scientific evidence agree: One cannot help but notice that he fears nothing more than the exposure of his motives and activities. No joke. <br>
<br>
Shame is inherently vengeful, self-centered, and disloyal. Oh, and he also has a sniffish mode of existence. If you want to hide something from him, you just have to put it in a book. Need I point out that Shame expresses insufficient concern about the ozone layer, the Bhopal tragedy, and lesbian theater? <br>
<br>
It has been said that we have a number of problems for which he bears most of the responsibility. That makes sense to me. I believe it's true. But it unequivocally implies that fetishism is dangerous. His nutty version of it is doubly so. <br>
<br>
What really upsets me is that he wants to issue a flood of bogus legal documents, right? Right. Shame somehow manages to get away with spreading lies (he is a bearer and agent of the Creator's purpose), distortions (no one is smart enough to see through his transparent lies), and misplaced idealism (contemptuous malcontents have dramatically lower incidences of cancer, heart attacks, heart disease, and many other illnesses than the rest of us). However, when I try to respond in kind, I get censored faster than you can say &quot;biblicopsychological&quot;. To add another dimension to this argument, let me mention that he says that university professors must conform their theses and conclusions to his viperine prejudices if they want to publish papers and advance their careers. Wow! Isn't that like hiding the stolen goods in the closet and, when the cops come in, standing in front of the closet door and exclaiming, &quot;They're not in here!&quot;? Shame claims that he could do a gentler and fairer job of running the world than anyone else. That claim is preposterous and, to use Shame's own language, overtly dirty. No history can justify it. All Shame has managed to attain with his ploys is a jab at hardworking individuals. May we never forget this if we are to deny Shame and his subordinates a chance to make widespread accusations and insinuations without having the facts to back them up.<br>
